83	\section{Monoidality of the categorical pull-back functor (Mathlib gap)}
84	
85	% NOTE: post-C1 named-deferred Mathlib gap. The Lean body is `sorry`; `\leanok` on the statement block reflects only well-formedness of the introduced declaration. Closure awaits either a Mathlib refresh landing `(SheafOfModules.pullback _).Monoidal` or a hand-construction of the tensor-preservation iso.
86	\begin{theorem}\leanok
87	[Pull-back of $\mathcal O$-modules preserves tensor product]
88	  \label{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}
89	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.SheafOfModules.pullback_tensorObj}
90	  \uses{def:Modules_tensorObj}
91	  Let $f \colon X \to Y$ be a morphism of schemes and $M, N \in Y.\mathrm{Modules}$. Then the categorical pull-back functor $f^* := \mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f$ preserves tensor products: there is a natural isomorphism
92	  \[
93	    f^*\bigl(M \otimes_{\mathcal O_Y} N\bigr) \;\cong\; f^* M \;\otimes_{\mathcal O_X}\; f^* N.
94	  \]
95	\end{theorem}
96	
97	\begin{proof}
98	  \uses{def:Modules_tensorObj, thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}
99	  This is the standard assertion that the inverse-image functor on $\mathcal O$-modules is monoidal. Mathlib provides $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f$ as a functor on quasi-coherent $\mathcal O$-modules and has the corresponding statement on the presheaf side, but \texttt{b80f227} does not register a $\mathrm{Functor.Monoidal}\,(\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f)$ instance. The proof proceeds by the tensor-hom adjunction together with the fact that the pull-back of the structure-sheaf-unit map is again a unit map; see Stacks~\texttt{01AC} and \S5 of Hartshorne~II for the affine-local picture. A future Mathlib refresh that lands $(\mathrm{SheafOfModules.pullback}\,\_).\mathrm{Monoidal}$ collapses this obligation to the canonical $\mathrm{MonoidalCategoryStruct.tensorObj}$-comparison.
100	\end{proof}
